characteristics.participants:
68 preterm infants as initial treatment of respiratory distress:
Inclusion criteria


GA at birth between 30 and 36 weeks and 6 days;

Appropriate weight for the gestational age;

Spontaneous breathing and clinical signs and symptoms of RDS.

Exclusion criteria


Major congenital abnormalities such as diaphragmatic hernia, cyanotic heart disease;

Intrauterine growth retardation;

Intubation and mandatory ventilation on the first day of life;

Perinatal asphyxia (umbilical cord pH < 7 and umbilical cord bicarbonate < 12 mEq/L).

characteristics.interventions:
Infants were randomised to initial mode of respiratory support:


nHFOV for initial treatment of respiratory distress (n = 34):nHFOV with initial settings: 

Pmean 8 cm H2O. Adjustments to the MAP were not permitted;

Frequency 10–20 Hz. Adjustments to the frequency were not permitted;

The amplitude was set at 20 cm H2O and adjusted (±2 cm H2O every 2 minutes), to maintain transcutaneous carbon dioxide (tcCO2) levels (40–60 mm Hg).

nCPAP for initial treatment of respiratory distress (n = 34)nCPAP initial settings: 

PEEP 6‐7 cm H2O;

Flow 7‐8 L/min.

A Fabian ventilator (Fabian, Autromic Medical Systems AG, Hirzel, Zurich, Switzerland) and binasal midline prongs (Fisher & Paykel Healthcare, New Zealand) were used for both groups. The FiO2was set to maintain SpO2at 89%–95%.

characteristics.outcomes:
Primary outcomes
The duration of using nCPAP or nHFOV.
Secondary outcomes


Failure of treatment defined as apnoea or pH < 7.2 and PaCO2> 60 mm Hg;

Need for intubation and ventilator when FiO2levels > 35% to maintain the desired oxygen saturation levels;

PDA;

Pulmonary haemorrhage;

NEC;

IVH;

CLD;

Pneumothorax;

Pulmonary haemorrhage;

Time to full enteral feeding.
